description:
TYPE SMELL: The module has 7 different step/event types with no shared base, despite all sharing the pattern {tick: number, description: string, ...domain-specific}:

- ThreadEvent: {tick, threadId, action, variable, value, description}
- BufferEvent: {tick, actor, action, item?, bufferState, bufferSize, description}
- PhilosopherEvent: {tick, philosopherId, state, forks, allForkStates, description, deadlock}
- EventLoopStep: {tick, description, state, highlight}
- GoroutineStep: {tick, goroutines, channels, description, action}
- RWEvent: {tick, actor, action, readerCount, writerActive, description}
- BarberEvent: {tick, barber, waitingRoom, capacity, customerAction, description}
- DeadlockStep: {tick, threads, resources, description, isDeadlocked}
- AsyncStep: {tick, pattern, promises, output?, description}
- MutexStep: {tick, threads, lockState, description, cpuCycles}
- PoolSnapshot: {tick, threads, queue, rejected, description}

All share {tick: number, description: string}. Extract:
```typescript
interface ConcurrencyStep {
  tick: number;
  description: string;
}

interface ThreadEvent extends ConcurrencyStep { threadId: string; action: ThreadAction; ... }
interface BufferEvent extends ConcurrencyStep { actor: string; action: BufferAction; ... }
// etc.
```

This enables generic playback utilities that work with any step type.

TYPE SAFETY: The useConcurrencyModule hook (ConcurrencyModule.tsx:2353-3188) manages state for ALL 11 demos simultaneously via separate useState/useMemo calls. When the active demo switches, the canvas renders based on a switch statement that selects the correct viz component. But there's no TYPE-LEVEL guarantee that the right data goes to the right viz.

Currently:
```typescript
// No type connection between 'active' and the data passed to each viz
const active: ConcurrencyDemo = 'race-condition';
const unsafeDemo = useMemo(() => unsafeIncrement(3, 3), []);
const pcEvents = useMemo(() => simulateProducerConsumer(2, 2, 4, 8), []);
// All computed simultaneously, switch selects which to render
```

Proposed discriminated union:
```typescript
type ActiveDemoData =
  | { type: 'race-condition'; unsafe: RaceConditionDemo; safe: RaceConditionDemo; histogram: number[] }
  | { type: 'producer-consumer'; events: BufferEvent[] }
  | { type: 'dining-philosophers'; naive: PhilosopherEvent[]; ordered: PhilosopherEvent[] }
  | { type: 'event-loop'; steps: EventLoopStep[]; demoId: EventLoopDemoId }
  // ... etc
```

This enables: (1) lazy computation of only the active demo's data, (2) TypeScript catches if you pass race-condition data to the producer-consumer viz, (3) cleaner switch exhaustiveness checking.

TYPE WEAKNESS: PhilosopherEvent.allForkStates is typed as string[] where values are 'free' | 'P0' | 'P1' | 'P2' | 'P3' | 'P4'. This string[] type loses all semantic meaning. Should be:

```typescript
type ForkOwner = `P${number}` | 'free';
// OR more precisely:
type ForkOwner = 'free' | 'P0' | 'P1' | 'P2' | 'P3' | 'P4';

interface PhilosopherEvent extends ConcurrencyStep {
  allForkStates: ForkOwner[]; // was string[]
  forks: [boolean, boolean];  // was boolean[] — always exactly 2 elements
}
```

Also: `forks: boolean[]` should be a tuple `[boolean, boolean]` since a philosopher always has exactly [left, right] — the array is always length 2.

CODE SMELL: goroutines.ts:103 uses `JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(obj))` for deep cloning. This is:
1. Slow (serialization round-trip)
2. Lossy (drops Date, Map, Set, undefined, functions, symbols)
3. Not type-safe (returns any from JSON.parse)

The cloned data is simple (Goroutine[], Channel[]) with only primitives and arrays, so it works — but `structuredClone()` is available in all modern browsers and is both faster and type-safe:

```typescript
// BEFORE (goroutines.ts:103)
function clone<T>(obj: T): T {
  return JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(obj));
}

// AFTER
function clone<T>(obj: T): T {
  return structuredClone(obj);
}
```

Note: structuredClone is available since Node 17 / all modern browsers.

EXTENSIBILITY: The switch statement in useConcurrencyModule for `canvas` rendering (ConcurrencyModule.tsx:2545-2650) and for `maxSteps` computation (line 2441-2466) have NO default/exhaustive check. If a developer adds a new demo ID to the ConcurrencyDemo union type, TypeScript will NOT warn that the switch statement is incomplete.

Add exhaustive checking:
```typescript
// AFTER each switch statement:
default: {
  const _exhaustiveCheck: never = active;
  throw new Error(`Unhandled demo: ${_exhaustiveCheck}`);
}
```

This makes adding a new demo type a compile error until all switch statements are updated.

TYPE DUPLICATION: Three sub-demo systems define similar but slightly different demo definition types:

```typescript
// event-loop.ts
interface EventLoopDemoDef { id: EventLoopDemoId; title: string; code: string; expectedOutput: string; }

// goroutines.ts
interface GoroutineDemoDef { id: GoroutineDemoId; title: string; code: string; }

// async-patterns.ts
interface AsyncPatternDef { id: AsyncPatternId; title: string; code: string; }

// ConcurrencyModule.tsx
interface DemoDef { id: ConcurrencyDemo; name: string; description: string; }
```

Four different structures for the same concept. Extract a generic:
```typescript
interface DemoDef<Id extends string> {
  id: Id;
  title: string;
  code?: string;
  description?: string;
  expectedOutput?: string;
}
```
